{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642339"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17934"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17934"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.05,0,0.7,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72912"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10648"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17934"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24806"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72912"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EObesity is a known risk factor for various types of cancer. Excess body weight can influence cancer risk through mechanisms such as hormone regulation, inflammation, and insulin resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor an otherwise well patient, with no other recognised risk factors, obesity can elevate the risk of certain cancers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Of which one of the following cancers would such patient be most at risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholangiocarcinoma","Lung cancer","Non-Hodgkin lymphoma","Pancreatic cancer","Renal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EObesity is a well-established risk factor for \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The increased risk is thought to be related to hormonal changes, chronic inflammation, and insulin resistance associated with excess body weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E - Primarily associated with smoking rather than obesity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-Hodgkin lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E - Not strongly linked to obesity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholangiocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E - More commonly associated with liver diseases and infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic cancer\u003C/strong\u003E - While obesity is a risk factor, renal cell carcinoma has a stronger association\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaintaining a healthy weight is important for reducing the risk of several cancers, including renal cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obesity is a significant risk factor for renal cell carcinoma.","Obesity is associated with an increased risk of several cancers, including breast, colorectal, and endometrial cancers.","Maintaining a healthy weight can reduce the risk of developing certain types of cancer."],"references":["Basen-Engquist K, Chang M. Obesity and cancer risk: recent review and evidence. Curr Oncol Rep. 2011 Feb;13(1):71-6. doi: 10.1007/s11912-010-0139-7. PMID: 21080117; PMCID: PMC3786180.","Pati S, Irfan W, Jameel A, Ahmed S, Shahid RK. Obesity and Cancer: A Current Overview of Epidemiology, Pathogenesis, Outcomes, and Management. Cancers (Basel). 2023 Jan 12;15(2):485. doi: 10.3390/cancers15020485. PMID: 36672434; PMCID: PMC9857053.","Bianchini F, Kaaks R, Vainio H. Overweight, obesity, and cancer risk. Lancet Oncol. 2002 Sep;3(9):565-74. doi: 10.1016/s1470-2045(02)00849-5. PMID: 12217794.","Graff RE, Wilson KM, Sanchez A, Chang SL, McDermott DF, Choueiri TK, Cho E, Signoretti S, Giovannucci EL, Preston MA. Obesity in Relation to Renal Cell Carcinoma Incidence and Survival in Three Prospective Studies. Eur Urol. 2022 Sep;82(3):247-251. doi: 10.1016/j.eururo.2022.04.032. Epub 2022 Jun 14. PMID: 35715363.","Venkatesh N, Martini A, McQuade JL, Msaouel P, Hahn AW. Obesity and renal cell carcinoma: Biological mechanisms and perspectives. Semin Cancer Biol. 2023 Sep;94:21-33. doi: 10.1016/j.semcancer.2023.06.001. Epub 2023 Jun 5. PMID: 37286114; PMCID: PMC10526958."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17934"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T14:59:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T14:59:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10648"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72912"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"g